  "text": "Depending on the extraction process used, PO contains 20-2,000 lg/L PL, whereas the polar lipid content of CO is negligible [CITATION_1] . As noted by [CITATION_2] , many freshwater fish species lack the ability to synthesis PL. Give the limited biosynthetic capacity of sunshine bass with respect to FA biotransformation, it is reasonable to assume that this hybrid species is also unable to meet PL requirements endogenously. Although [CITATION_3] demonstrated growth performance of sunshine bass was unaffected by dietary supplementation with soy lecithin (as a source of phosphatidylcholine), the basal diet contained approximately 7%-PL-rich FO, and was probably sufficient to meet the PL requirement of these fish without the addition of lecithin. Although the PL requirement may be lower among juvenile and subadult individuals compared with larval fish [CITATION_4] , sunshine bass undoubtedly exhibit some nominal requirement for PL throughout their life cycle. Unfortunately, few studies have evaluated the PL requirements of fish beyond the early juvenile stages, and none have addressed this question in the context of sunshine bass nutrition. Although some alternative lipid sources provide considerable amounts of PL (e.g., soybean-and canola-derived feedstuffs), others may be limited or wholly deficient with respect to this nutrient [CITATION_5] ). Additional research is needed to establish the PL requirement of sunshine bass (and other species) at the juvenile and subadult stages to assess the potential for PL deficiency in alternative lipid-based aquafeeds.",
